1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. cxd5 exd5 {Here this version of the
central exchange seems innocuous for Black, who has made the useful c7-c6 move
instead of Bf8-e7, for instance. As the d5-pawn is overprotected, his task is
to solve the problem with Bc8, so} 6. Qc2 {is aimed against its comfortable
appearance at the f5-square.} (6. g3 $6 {is not the most successful plan, for
the fianchettoed bishop will be faced to the enemy pawn chain.} Bf5 7. Bg2 (7.
Nh4 Be6 {is likely to transpose}) 7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nh4 Be6 10. Qc2 (10.
Bg5 Be7) 10... Nbd7 11. Nf5 Bc7 $15 {[%cal Gf8e8]}) (6. e3 {secures the
d3-square for the pwn bishop, but locks the other one. Black has once again an
easy development -} Bd6 (6... Bf5 7. Nh4 Be6 8. Bd3 Bd6 $11) 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2
Re8 9. O-O Na6 (9... Bg4 $5) 10. a3 (10. Bxa6 bxa6 $132 {[%csl Gc8,Gd6]}) 10...
Nc7 $132) (6. Bg5 {is more to the point and then} h6 $1 {is a sensible reply:}
