1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Qd3 {White clearly declares his
intention to execute the central advance e2-e4 as quickly as possible.} (5. Qb3
dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {does not differ at all.}) 5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3 (7. Qb3
{is an alternative again, White is facing another choice after} Nbd7 (7... a6
$5 8. e4 c5) 8. g3 {has a lot of similarities with the Catalan lines with an
early queen check from a4, by which White immediately regains the c4-pawn,
though afterward the b3-square, is not the preferred square for a retreat and
the second player can benefit:} (8. Bg5 a6 9. e4 (9. e3 Bb7 10. Be2 c5 $15)
9... c5 10. d5 c4 11. Qc2 Be7 12. a4 Bb7 $132) (8. Bf4 {is also answered with}
a6 {, getting prepared for the thematic c6-c5}) (8. e4 $2 {cannot be
recommended here -} b4 9. Na4 {and, compared to the leading text with 7.Qd3,
there is} Nxe4 10. Qc2 ({otherwise White will be just a pawn down, e.g.} 10.
Bd3 Nef6 11. O-O Bd6 $17) 10... Nef6 11. Qxc6 Rb8 12. Ba6 {(preventing
12...Bb7, but the trade of the light-squared bishops is coming in handy for
Black)} Bxa6 13. Qxa6 Qc8 14. Qxc8+ Rxc8 {with pleasant positional advantage
for Black, who will soon enjoy a marvelous Nd5 against a counterpart on the
a4-square}) 8... b4 $5 {is more straightforward -} (8... Bb7 9. Bg2 a6 {
is a calm way to prepare gradually the c6-c5 push, e.g.} 10. Ne5 Qc8 11. O-O c5
12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. dxc5 (13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bg5 {should not disturb
Black, for instance} O-O 16. Bxf6 gxf6 $132) 13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Bxc5 15. Bg5
O-O ({indeed,} 15... Be7 {is fully playable}) 16. Bxf6 Qb7+ 17. f3 gxf6 18. Ne4
Be7 $11) 9. Na4 c5 (9... Ba6) (9... Qa5) 10. Bg2 ({Black has a comfortable
equality after} 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Nxc5 Bxc5 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Bb7 14. Bg2
Qb6) 10... Bb7 11. O-O (11. Nxc5 Nxc5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Qa4+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7
15. O-O Ke7 {looks roughly equal, but White has successfully traded both
problematic pieces from the queenside}) 11... Bd5 {Here it is - by attacking
Qb3, Black has every chance to take over the initiative.} 12. Qd1 (12. Qc2 $6
Rc8) (12. Qe3 c4 13. a3 bxa3 14. bxa3 Bd6 $132) 12... Rc8 (12... c4 $5 13. a3
$140 a5 $36) 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Bd2 Ncd7 ({if Black (correctly!) wishes to leave
Na4 at the edge of the board, then the textmove is better than} 14... Nce4 15.
Be3) 15. Nd4 (15. Rc1 Be7 {is likely to transpose}) 15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Be7 17.
Rc1 Ne5 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. Qb3 O-O {with comfortable equality.}) 7... Bb7 {
The best continuation - the bishops belong to the big diagonal and, depending
on the opponent's actions, Black will either prepare c6-c5 by 8....a6 or carry
it out as in the text.} ({In case of the immediate} 7... a6 {even} 8. g4 $5 {
can be expected}) ({Black's task is more difficult after} 7... Nbd7 8. e4 b4 9.
Na4 {as well.}) 8. e4 {Consequent, though Black is well armored to meet it.} ({
The preliminary} 8. a3 {is harmless -} a6 9. e4 c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8
12. Bd3 h6 $11) (8. Bg5 Nbd7 9. e4 (9. g3 a6 10. Bg2 c5 11. O-O Rc8 $11) 9...
b4 10. Na4 Qa5 11. b3 c5 12. Bxf6 ({the queenside knight has been chased to
the edge of the board, therefore} 12. d5 $6 {is a wrong idea - after} exd5 13.
exd5 Bd6 {the central pawn is in danger}) 12... gxf6 (12... Nxf6 $2 {loses the
c5-pawn -} 13. Qb5+) 13. Be2 ({Black is at least equal after the new central
break} 13. d5 $6 O-O-O $1 14. dxe6 $140 Nb6 $1 15. Nxb6+ Qxb6 {; the opening
of the center suits him well either}) 13... cxd4 14. O-O (14. Qxd4 Rd8 {
with excellent play for Black due to his better coordinated minor pieces, so
is in the text}) 14... Be7 15. Nxd4 Rd8 $132) 8... b4 9. Na4 (9. Nd1 $6 {
does not challenge the liberating c6-c5 at all. so} Nbd7 10. Ne3 c5 $15) 9...
Qa5 10. b3 c5 $1 ({There is no need to delay the thematic break in favour of}
10... Nbd7 $6 {, which is aimed against White's next textmove, but after} 11.
Bf4 c5 {Nf3 has another route to the c4-square.}) 11. Ne5 {Besides, White has
a large choice between:} ({Black is absolutely fine after} 11. Qb5+ Qxb5 12.
Bxb5+ Bc6 13. Bxc6+ Nxc6 14. e5 (14. dxc5 Nxe4) 14... Nd7 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16.
dxc5 Bxc5 17. Bb2 O-O-O 18. Rc1 Rd5 19. Ke2 Kb7 $11) (11. d5 exd5 12. exd5 Bd6
({safer than} 12... Bxd5 13. Bg5 Nbd7 14. O-O-O $13) 13. Qb5+ (13. Bb2 Nbd7)
13... Qxb5 14. Bxb5+ Nbd7 15. Be3 O-O $11) (11. dxc5 $6 Bxe4 12. Qb5+ Qxb5 13.
Bxb5+ Bc6 {has led to a fantastic blockading position after} 14. Nd4 Bxb5 15.
Nxb5 Nd5 16. Bb2 Nc6 $15 {in L. Danov - D. Andreikin, Struga, 2021}) ({
alternatively,} 11. Nxc5 Bxc5 12. dxc5 {is strongly countered with} Nxe4 $1
$146 (12... Bxe4 $143 13. Qb5+ Qxb5 14. Bxb5+ Bc6 15. Be2 {and the c5-pawn is
very alive and kicking}) (12... O-O 13. Nd2 {is also preventing Black's most
direct way to harass it}) 13. Nd2 (13. c6 Bxc6 $140 14. Nd4 {is an interesting,
though probably insufficient, pawn sacrifice, for example} Bd5 15. f3 Nd6 16.
Bf4 Qb6 $15) ({Black has little to worry about in case of} 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Qd4
Nc3 15. a3 Nc6 16. Qc4 Nd5 17. axb4 Qxb4+ 18. Nd2 a5 {with good prospects on
the queenside}) ({the c6-pawn seems doomed after} 13. Qb5+ Qxb5 14. Bxb5+ Ke7
15. Nd4 Rc8) 13... Nxc5 (13... Nxd2 14. Bxd2 Nc6 $11) 14. Qg3 O-O 15. Bb2 f6
16. Nc4 Qd8 {and, although White has some initiative, he has to prove
compensation for the pawn after} 17. Be2 Nbd7 18. O-O Nb6) (11. e5 Ba6 $1 12.
Qc2 (12. Qd1 $6 Nd5) 12... Bxf1 13. Kxf1 (13. Rxf1 $6 Nd5 14. Bd2 Nd7 15. Rc1
Rc8 $15 {Stocek - Anton Guijarro, Czech Republic, 2019}) 13... Nd5 {is a very
nice version (thus the exchange of the light-squared bishops has fortified the
perfect location of Nd5) of the standard Meran, no matter how White is going
to take:} 14. Nxc5 (14. dxc5 Nd7 15. c6 N7b6 (15... Nc5 {Rc8 is a sound
alternative}) 16. Nxb6 axb6 17. h4 (17. Bd2 Bc5) 17... Qc5 $11) 14... Bxc5 15.
Qxc5 (15. dxc5 Nc3) 15... Qxc5 16. dxc5 Na6 ({a blockading plan with} 16... Nc6
17. Bd2 a5 $44 {has the right to exist, though Black can regain the pawn and
fight for the c-file}) 17. c6 Rc8 $11) 11... cxd4 ({The consistent move, as}
11... Bxe4 $6 {is leaving the same pawn under attack, after} 12. Qb5+ Qxb5 13.
Bxb5+ Nbd7 {there is even} 14. Bf4 $5 cxd4 $140 15. Rc1 $36) 12. Qb5+ {Yet
another indisputably best move, as confirmed by:} ({White has to show
something for the pawn after} 12. Qxd4 $6 Bxe4) ({The same is valid for} 12.
Bf4 Nxe4 {e.g.} 13. Rc1 Nc3 14. Qxd4 f6 15. Nc4 Qd5 {etc.}) 12... Qxb5 13.
Bxb5+ Nfd7 $1 $146 (13... Ke7 {allows} 14. Nc5 $1 Bxe4 15. Bb2 $36 {Andreikin -
Anand, Moscow, 2013.}) 14. Bb2 {The logical follow-up,White's most active
pieces will be chased after the other options:} (14. O-O f6) (14. Bd2 Ba6 $1)
14... Bd6 15. Bxd4 ({White can hardly progress by} 15. Nc4 Be7 16. Ne5 $140 ({
for} 16. Bxd4 Bxe4 {see 16.Nc4 below}) 16... Bf6 $5 (16... Bd6 $11) 17. Nxd7
Nxd7 18. Rc1 {and he must think how to meet the intended e6-e5 after} Bc8 ({
but not} 18... Rc8 $2 19. Nc5 $36 Bc6 20. Nd3 {and White regains the pawn with
interest, for instance} Bb7 21. Rxc8+ Bxc8 22. e5 Be7 23. Bxd4)) 15... Bxe4 16.
Nxd7 (16. O-O {is the main alternative, Black seems to be in full order after}
Ke7 17. Rfe1 ({in reply to} 17. Nc4 {there is the simplifying} Bd3 18. Rfe1
Bxc4 19. Bxc4 Nb6 20. Nxb6 axb6 21. Bxg7 Rg8 22. Bh6 Nd7 $11) 17... Bxe5 18.
Bxe5 Nxe5 19. Rxe4 Nbd7 20. Bxd7 Nxd7 21. Rxb4 Rhb8 $11) (16. Nc4 $143 $6 Be7 {
and after} 17. O-O {Black can also castle with a healthy pawn up.}) (16. Nc5 {
at once allows} Bxc5 17. Bxc5 Nc6 $1 {and it is White, who has to be on alert:}
18. Nxd7 (18. Nxc6 Nxc5 19. Rc1 a6 20. Rxc5 axb5 21. Nxb4 Bxg2 22. Rg1 Be4 23.
Re5 (23. Rxb5 O-O 24. Rc5 Rfd8 25. Ke2 Rdb8 26. Rc4 Bd5) 23... Bf5 24. Rxb5 {
and here Black can spare time on castling and send a warning to the enemy
monarch by} Rc8) 18... Kxd7 19. f3 Bd5 20. Bxb4 ({to} 20. Ba6 {the simplest is}
Nb8 21. Bb5+ Nc6 $11 {, just repeating}) 20... Rhb8 {forces} 21. Bxc6+ {
, when it is time to sign a draw}) 16... Nxd7 17. Nc5 (17. f3 Bd5 {will most
probably transpose.}) 17... Bxc5 18. Bxc5 Rb8 19. Ba4 Rb7 20. f3 Bd5 21. Rc1
Kd8 22. Bd4 Ke7 {This one and Black's next move can be played in reversed
