1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Bd2 (6. h3 Bd6 7. Bd3 (7.
g4 $6 {is too optimistic, albeit a trendy push -} O-O $15) 7... O-O 8. O-O ({
In reply to} 8. e4 {Black has a tempting choice between two systems in the
Meran, in which h2-h3 may not be useful -} dxc4 $5 ({a solid alternative is}
8... dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 e5 11. Qc2 h6 $11) 9. Bxc4 e5 10. O-O exd4 11.
Nxd4 (11. Qxd4 Qe7 12. Rd1 Bc7 $11) 11... Nc5 12. Re1 Re8 {with approximate
equality after a couple of fireworks -} 13. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 14. e5 Ba6 $1 15. Bxa6
$140 Bxe5 16. Bc4 Qb6 $11) 8... dxc4 {(a similar approach)} 9. Bxc4 b5 10. Bd3
(10. Be2 b4 11. Na4 Bb7 12. b3 c5 13. Bb2 Qe7 $11) 10... b4 11. Ne4 (11. Ne2 c5
12. e4 cxd4 13. Nexd4 Bb7 14. Re1 Qa5 $11) 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bb7 13. Nd2 (13.
b3 Nf6 14. Bd3 c5 $11) 13... Ba6 $1 {An adequate reaction to White's most
dangerous strategic plan. Indeed, it is never easy to play a second move in a
row with one and the same piece, but it is essential to deprive the knight of
the c4-square.} 14. Re1 ({Black's last instructive sally actually contains a
pawn sacrifice -} 14. Bxc6 Rc8 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. Re1 Bb7 {with huge play due
to the powerful bishops, e.g.} 17. b3 Bb8 18. Nc4 f5 $44) 14... Rc8 15. a3 (15.
Bf3 c5 16. Ne4 Bb8 $11) 15... Bb5 16. axb4 (16. Nf3 a5 17. b3 c5 $11) 16...
Bxb4 {with ample compensation for the pawn after} 17. Rxa7 c5 $11) (6. Ne5 Bb4
({an interesting concrete idea, there is also} 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Nd7 8. f4 Be7
9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O f6 $11) 7. Bd2 {An attention should be paid to 7...Ne4.} O-O
{Black keeps the pace to develop a piece by each move, the opponent is not
going to enjoy the pair of bishops for long after} 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Nxe5 10.
dxe5 Ne4 11. Qc2 $140 b6 $11) (6. a4 {is inviting} Bb4 $5 ({for details about}
6... Bd6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O {see the next Chapters}) 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O b6 9. Qc2
Bb7 10. b3 Qe7 11. Bb2 Rfd8 $11) (6. a3 Bd6 7. Bd3 (7. c5 $6 Bc7 8. b4 O-O 9.
Bb2 Re8 $15) 7... O-O 8. O-O Re8 $5 (8... e5 {can be executed at once}) ({
Black cannot employ the plan with} 8... dxc4 {to the same extent as against
6.h3, for it is impossible for the moment to chase Nc3 in that line from above}
) 9. e4 (9. Qc2 e5 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. e4 ({this push leads to simplifications
in the center and an almost inevitable draw; in the next Chapter we are going
to see a similar position with} 11. Nb5 {, but with White's bishops on d2 and
e2 respectively; the game can continue with} Bb8 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5
14. Bd2 Bd7 $132 {and after} 15. Bc3 Rc8 {White does not have the luxury to
occupy the d4-square; besides, he must also reckon with the typical bishop
