1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd2 {We have
already seen White's minor alternatives after 6.Bd2 Bd6, the moment has come
to see the main plan with Qd1-c2 and castling to the long, after which e3-e4
will be in the air. But let us first look at the direct central advance:} (7.
e4 $6 Nxe4 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Qxe4 e5 $1 10. dxe5 (10. Nxe5 O-O 11. Bd3 g6 12.
Nxd7 Bxd7 13. O-O Re8 14. Qf3 Qh4 15. g3 Qxd4 $15) (10. c5 Bc7 11. dxe5 Nxc5
$15) 10... O-O 11. exd6 ({this continuation, which contains an early queen
sacrifice, is the main theoretical continuation for years on end. Harmless is}
11. Be2 Re8 $15) ({, while} 11. Bd3 f5 $1 {assures Black of comfortable
equality after} 12. Qe2 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. O-O Re8 15. Qf3 Qf6 16. Rb1 Be6
17. Bf4 Bxf4 18. Qxf4 Rad8 $11) 11... Re8 12. Qxe8+ Qxe8+ 13. Be3 Ne5 14. Be2 (
14. O-O-O $144 Bg4) 14... Bg4 15. O-O-O Qe6 16. Rhe1 Nxf3 17. gxf3 Bf5 18. Bf1
Qf6 19. c5 h5 20. Bc4 Re8 $15) 7... O-O 8. O-O-O (8. Bd3 {is a different story,
after} dxc4 9. Bxc4 b5 {we have almost reached the main Meran, in which Black
will try to prove that Bc1-d2 has been a waste of time:} 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 Bb7
11. O-O Qb8 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gc6c5]} 12. Ne4 ({the hidden purpose behind
Black's last mysterious move is revealed after} 12. e4 c5 $1 {and Black has
little to worry about in the forced line} 13. e5 cxd4 14. exf6 dxc3 15. fxg7
Rc8 16. bxc3 Nf6 $132) (12. a3 a5) 12... Nxe4 13. Qxe4 c5 {comes in time again
-} 14. Qh4 h6 $11) 10... Bb7 11. a3 (11. O-O $6 {is met by} b4 12. Ne4 ({
yet another important line is} 12. Na4 c5 $1 13. dxc5 Rc8 $15 {, when the
greedy} 14. Bxb4 $2 {is refuted by} Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nd5 $19 {[%cal Gd8h4]}) 12...
Nxe4 13. Bxe4 f5 14. Bd3 c5 $15) (11. e4 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 {
is more or less balanced after} 14. f4 ({Black is absolutely fine in case of}
14. O-O a6 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 15. Rad1 c5 $132) 14... Bxc3 15. Bxc3 c5 16. Bxb5 (
16. e5 c4) (16. Rd1 Qb6) 16... Nxe4 $11) (11. Ng5 h6 12. Nge4 Be7 13. Nxf6+
Nxf6 14. Ne4 {and here} c5 $1 {is the equalizer, e.g.} 15. dxc5 Nxe4 16. Bxe4
Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Bxc5 $11) {, as usual, is answered with} 11... a5 {, thus
resuming the idea to push the b-pawn. Here are several sample lines, where, in
comparison to the lines from above attention will be paid to the ones, in
which White is castling earlier:} 12. Ng5 (12. O-O b4 13. axb4 axb4 14. Ne4
Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 16. Bd3 c5 17. Rxa8 (17. dxc5 Rc8 18. Bxb4 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nd5
$132) 17... Qxa8 18. dxc5 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Qxf3 20. cxd6 Qg4+ $11) 12... h6 13.
Nge4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Be7 15. O-O {and the resolute strike} c5 $1 {comes again
into the limelight with satisfactory play in all the lines -} 16. Nxc5 (16.
Bxb5 cxd4 17. exd4 Nf6 18. Nc5 Qd5 19. Nxb7 Qxb5 20. Nc5 Rfd8 21. Be3 Nd5 $44)
(16. dxc5 f5 $1 17. c6 $140 Rc8 18. Qb3 Bxc6 19. Qxe6+ Rf7 20. Bxa5 Qxa5 21.
Ng3 Kf8 22. Nxf5 Qa8 $15) 16... Nxc5 17. dxc5 Qd5 18. f3 Rfd8 19. Be4 Qxc5 20.
Qxc5 Bxc5 21. Bxb7 Ra7 $11) 8... e5 {Black is the first one to strike at the
center, we stick to this push again.} ({Alternatively, there is also} 8... c5)
({or the preparatory} 8... Re8) ({, while} 8... b5 $5 {offers a real gambit -}
9. cxb5 c5 {etc.}) 9. cxd5 (9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. Kb1 Re8 $132) 9...
cxd5 10. Nb5 (10. dxe5 $6 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Kb1 Be6 $15) 10... Bb8 11.
dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 (12. Bc3 $6 {appears to be premature because of the strong
intermezzo} a6 $1 13. Nbd4 (13. Nxe5 axb5 $17) 13... Ne4 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Nc6
bxc6 16. Bxe5 Re8 $15 {[%cal Gc8f5] and, after Bc8 joins the rest of his army,
White will most probably regret about his optimistic plan with castling to the
long.}) 12... Bxe5 13. Kb1 (13. f4 Bb8 $132) (13. Bc3 {looks strategically
sound, but things are far from easy after} Qe7 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 15.
Qc3 Qg5 {Of course, the queens should be kept on the board. This time, White
is not in such danger of being mated after} 16. Kb1 Bd7 17. Nd4 {, he
experiences serious difficulties with the mobilization of his kingside after}
Ne4 18. Qe1 Rfe8 $15) (13. f3 {is preventing the annoying jump, but at the
cost of weakening the own s3-pawn, Black's chances are not worse -} Be6 14. Bc3
Bxc3 15. Nxc3 Rc8 16. Rd4 Nd7 17. Kb1 Ne5 $132 {[%cal Gd8a5]}) 13... Be6 14.
Bd3 Rc8 (14... a6 15. Bc3 axb5 16. Bxe5 Qa5 17. b3 Ne4 $11) 15. Qa4 ({It is
amazing, but the most natural move} 15. Bc3 $6 {appears to be untimely again,
here, the reason is the sound pawn sacrifice} Qb6 16. Nd4 Ne4 $1 17. Bxe4 dxe4
18. Qxe4 Rfe8 19. Qc2 {with a huge play on the queenside in return for it -} a5
20. Ka1 a4 $40) 15... Qd7 (15... a6 16. Nd4 Bd7 17. Qb3 Ne4 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19.
Qxb7 Bxd4 20. exd4 Bg4 21. Rc1 Qxd4 {has resulted in a balanced position with
opposite-coloured bishops and no weaknesses, when the draw looks inevitable -}
22. Be3 Qd3+ 23. Ka1 h6 $11) 16. f4 ({A concession, but Black has the playing
initiative after} 16. Bc3 Ng4 $1) 16... Bd6 17. Bc3 Be7 18. Qc2 a6 19. Nd4 Ne4
20. Bxe4 dxe4 21. Nxe6 Qxe6 $11 *

