Bf8 $1 25. Qxf7+ $140 Qxf7 26. Bxf7+ Kxf7 27. Rd7+ Kxf6 28. Rxb7 Bd6 {,
reaching a promising ending}) {and it is important that} 22. Bxf6 $6 {leads to
nowhere after} Qxf6 23. Qh7+ Kf8 24. Re1 g5 $1) 16... h6 17. Bxh6 gxh6 18. Qxh6
{is more frightening than ever, but Black has the spectacular rook manoeuvre}
Re8 $1 19. Ng5 Re4 $1 ({limiting the scope of Bd3 rather than allowing} 19...
Rc7 20. Bh7+ Kh8 21. Bf5+ Kg8 22. Nh7 $16 {[%cal Gd1d3]}) 20. Bxe4 dxe4 21. Nh7
$1 (21. a4 Rc7 $1 {[%cal Gc7d7]}) (21. f3 $6 Qe7) 21... Nxh7 $5 ({Black. if he
wishes so, can make a silent draw offer by} 21... Ne8 22. Ng5 Nf6 $11) 22. Rxd6
Qg5 $1 23. Qxg5+ Nxg5 24. Rd7 Bc6 ({the more passive} 24... Rb8 {must also
work, for instance} 25. Rad1 Ne6 $11 {[%cal Gg8f8]}) 25. Rxa7 Rd8 26. h4 Ne6
27. Ra6 Rd2 28. Rxb6 Nd4 {Black has activated his pieces to the utmost; he has
a draw in his pocket at least, for example} 29. a4 e3 30. fxe3 Rxg2+ 31. Kf1
Nc2 32. Rxc6 Nxe3+ 33. Ke1 Nc2+ 34. Kf1 (34. Kd1 Nxa1 35. Rxc5 Rxb2 $11) 34...
Ne3+ $11) 7... O-O 8. O-O e5 $5 ({Another important theoretical line is} 8...
dxc4 9. Bxc4 {and now 9...a6 or 9...b5.}) 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. e4 {Causing crisis
in the center.} (10. Nb5 {An essential alternative is} Bb8 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12.
Nxe5 Bxe5 {, when, given the fact White has not wasted time on rare 5th moves (
see Chapter 5) , he can fight for the key d4-square.} 13. Bd2 {is the logical
continuation, the bishop is on its way to the longest diagonal.} (13. h3 a6 (
13... Bd7) (13... Re8) 14. Nd4 Re8 15. Bd2 Ne4 $11) (13. f4 Bb8 14. Bd2 a6 15.
Nd4 Re8 $11 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4]}) 13... a6 14. Bc3 (14. Nd4 Ne4 $5 (14...
Re8 15. Nf3 Bd6 16. Rfd1 Bg4 17. Be2 Ne4 18. Be1 $14) 15. Bxe4 (15. Rad1 Re8)
15... dxe4 16. Qxe4 {We have already seen (iv Chapter 10) of this pawn
