1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. a4 {The last
real possibility to deviate from the main lines of the Botvinnik variation. It
is well-known that 7...Bb4 is not Black's best choice because of 8.e5 g5 9.exf6
gxh4 10.fxg7 Rg8 11.g3 or 11.h4, but the second player has sound alternatives
at his disposal. Let us have at first a look at a minor option of White's,
which does not harass the b5-pawn:} (7. Be2 $6 Be7 (7... h6 $5) 8. O-O O-O 9.
b3 (9. Qc2 Nbd7 $15) 9... b4 (9... cxb3 $5 10. axb3 h6 $15) 10. e5 Nd5 11. Bxe7
Nxe7 (11... Qxe7 12. Nxd5 cxd5 {is probably Black's most solid reaction - he
is giving the extra pawn back in return for a safe middlegame, in which he
will rely on his queenside majority in the long run -} 13. bxc4 dxc4 14. Bxc4
Bb7 15. d5 exd5 16. Bxd5 Nc6 $11) 12. Ne4 cxb3 (12... c3 $6 13. a3) 13. Qxb3
Ba6 14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. Rfc1 Rb8 $15) 7... b4 $5 {Launching a counterattack on
the queenside is the most ambitious option.} ({The main theoretical
continuation is} 7... Qb6 8. Be2 Nbd7) 8. Nb1 {The other retreats can hardly
be recommended:} (8. Na2 $6 Ba6 9. Rc1 Qb6 10. Bxf6 (10. Bxc4 Nxe4 $15) 10...
gxf6 11. Bxc4 Bh6 $1 {[%csl Rc1]} 12. O-O Bxc1 13. Qxc1 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 a5 $15) (
